<br>
BUT a better way to approach is sure I could bring a 50 druid is that cool? And then once you're in, ask hey whats this big ugly drop thats good for druids, and strike up a friendly converstaion with the druids perhaps about it, raid leaders got enough going on with answering 50 players questions about loot. Sooner or later they will get tired and shut you out.<br>
<br>
And an even better way to ensure loot is build a reputation. Ask politely about it once in, and if you dont get any, dont gripe. People will remember your positive attitude, and be more inclined to reward it with loot, well if theyre any good<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   And if this cat Jakle has been doing this a while, and has a good rep, chances are he will or others will and mention to him, well they will remember you. <br>
<br>
If you cussed at him in guild chat, that was a bad approach too. Next time dont ask about loot until in the raid, and then be careful. I wouldnt ask till I had a few raids under my belt and knew me a little. Then I would phrase it, if I didnt know(after looking online or asking someone after the raid, usually another monk) in group usually, hey whats cazic drop? And ask about all the loot, and they listed a darkwood trunk, a wr container. They would also mention it was good for monks, and I said rock on! <br>
<br>
Anyway, its all about approach man. Even after booted from chat, when you got back in say hey Im sorry if I annoyed ya, 50druid services still available, just let me know. Then join your group with your 42pally, letting them know, &quot;hey guys I may join the gor raid if they need my 50 druid. Is it cool to kill with you guys until then? Or would you rather I wait to know for sure?&quot;<br>
<br>
Just a few ways you couldve handled it, you arent wrong to want loot or be concerned or question about it, but its all in the way you go about it. Leading, and organizing raids can be frustrating, tiring, stressful, and thankless work. So give Jakle the benefit of the doubt and just apologize for any misbehavior and or misperceptions. Chances are if hes any good he will apologize too or accept your apology once the raids done, or a little times passed. <br>
<br>
A posted apology on what you thought to be a misunderstanding perhaps? as opposed to a semi flame towards him.<br>
<br>
But no, you werent wrong in your intent, Id say more your approach.<br>
<br>
/shrug<br>
<br>
Peace<br>
<br>
Edit: I agree with Balrak, agreat many people who are old and gray veterans now once were noobs asking that same question. I tolerated it, you can too. The leaders and more experienced players should temper their actions/words/decisions with understanding, compassion, wisdom and such. You know young players may be excited and not be the most tactful or use whats considered proper etiquette, but then again I didnt get an etiquette manual at 14 or whatever, and it didnt come when I got eq either. So freaking grow up as well and realize the question may arise, whats in it for me? <br>
<br>
Personally, I think a more mature thing to do, and one that would earn you the respect of that young player would be send em a tell, or let em know. &quot;hey man, its cool youre excited about possibly joining a dragon and killing her, and getting some loot, but there is a better way to go about introducing yourself then...whats she drop for me?&quot; Instead of branding them a loot whore and going off on some holier then thou etiquette tangent.<br>
